@Crispy1975, thanks for the doc updates. This is looking good. As I consider this further, one nagging question keeps popping into my head, and that is one of whether the value of the `X-Frame-Options` header is better configured per Deis application rather than router-wide. By contrast, disabling server tokens router-wide makes sense to me because that seems like something an ops person would _want_ to enforce cluster-wide if policy dictates. But when it comes to `X-Frame-Options`, I could very easily see application-specific values being necessary. While one application might require `DENY` for security reasons, another, might (let's say a SPA) might require `SAMEORIGIN`, and yet a third (let's say an ad server) might require that this not be restricted.

Obviously, making this configurable per application is a great deal more work, but I also want to make sure we're not hastily adding a feature that impairs overall flexibility.

The possibility also exists that, since we've gotten by without any explicit support for `X-Frame-Options` up until now, that we should continue to do so. I do believe that applications that must set a particular value in that header for one reason or another can easily do so themselves, and the value should pass through in the proxied response.

