@androguard/external-contributors anyone has an idea how to deal with this problem?
Here is a short recap:
* Internally, we can use unicode strings, no matter what is in there. In my opinion, the MUTF8 decoder works correctly in this respect.
* Not all strings are well behaved strings, ie if only a sole high or low surrogate is passed, the decoding will not work
* To be able to print strings, we need to merge surrogate pairs into a single 32bit character, ie `\uD853\uDF5C` must be written as `\u0024F5C` to be printable. Both `\uD853` and `\uDF5C` can never be printed.
The interesting thing is, that it will work in Java:
```
class Test{
        public static void main(String[] args){
                String s = "\uD853";
                System.out.println(s);
        }
}
```
