It is working because the **images are loaded on the fly (when they are needed)**, e.g. if you call X[1] it will load the image. That is why you dont see a ndarray of images after initiliazing the preloader but just a list of image paths. 

This is really the expected behaviour, since you would use the image_preloader if you want to handle large datasets (hence you do not want to load them all at once at the beginning).

If you are interested in how this is implemented. You first have to look in data_utils.py at the base [class Preloader](https://github.com/tflearn/tflearn/blob/3579931c121b228e00691f714b5ac0eb1b5e2c2e/tflearn/data_utils.py#L799-L813) and more specifically the function 
```python
 def __getitem__(self, id):
        if type(id) in [list, np.ndarray]:
            return [self.function(self.array[i]) for i in id]
        elif isinstance(id, slice):
            return [self.function(arr) for arr in self.array[id]]
        else:
return self.function(self.array[id])
```
This is where the [ ] operator is overloaded. Here you see that the function `self.function(arr)` is called. Now in implementation classes of the Preloader this function can be registered.
For example if you look at the class [ImagePreloader](https://github.com/tflearn/tflearn/blob/3579931c121b228e00691f714b5ac0eb1b5e2c2e/tflearn/data_utils.py#L816)

```python
class ImagePreloader(Preloader):
    def __init__(self, array, image_shape, normalize=True, grayscale=False):
        fn = lambda x: self.preload(x, image_shape, normalize, grayscale)
super(ImagePreloader, self).__init__(array, fn)
```
There the function 'self.preload' is registered. And finally you can look at this function to see what is actually happening when an item from an ImagePreloader is requested.
```python
 def preload(self, path, image_shape, normalize=True, grayscale=False):
        img = load_image(path)
        width, height = img.size
        if width != image_shape[0] or height != image_shape[1]:
            img = resize_image(img, image_shape[0], image_shape[1])
        if grayscale:
            img = convert_color(img, 'L')
        img = pil_to_nparray(img)
        if normalize:
            img /= 255.
return img
```

I managed to create a test case which doesn't depend on pybind11 and which compiles with g++ 6.4.0 and clang 5.0.1 but not with VS2017 15.5.6: 

```
#include <type_traits>
#include <cstddef>

using namespace std;

struct S
{
  void operator delete(void*) = delete;
  void operator delete(void*, std::size_t) = delete;
};

template <class T, typename SFINAE = void> struct has_operator_delete : std::false_type { };
template <class T> class has_operator_delete<T, void_t<
  decltype(static_cast<void(*)(void*)>(T::operator delete))>> : std::true_type { };

template <class T, class SFINAE = void> struct has_operator_delete_size : std::false_type { };
template <class T> struct has_operator_delete_size<T, void_t<
  decltype(static_cast<void(*)(void*, std::size_t)>(T::operator delete))>> : std::true_type { };

int main()
{
  static_assert(!has_operator_delete<S>::value);
  static_assert(!has_operator_delete_size<S>::value);
}
```

With VS2017 15.5.6 both asserts fail. [I reported the issue to Microsoft.](https://developercommunity.visualstudio.com/content/problem/201249/sfinae-failure-with-void-t-decltype-and-operator-d.html)

See 6a57cc5.  (I'll investigate the MSVC failure).

One thing that concerns me in this is having to make [this change](https://github.com/pybind/pybind11/pull/400/commits/6a57cc521317719e3b7858c3ee1c720474adbff8#diff-a78501166035cfaf04f078075e1ffc3dR23).  Without it, the associated test would fail because the C++ class was doing essentially:

```C++
"{} {}"_s.format(get_string1(), *get_string2())
```

and since `format` takes arguments by reference, this ends up passing two references to the same string into `format`, which happily prints the same string twice.  Oops.

It's not hard to envision a fairly innocent C++ class that this is going to break:
```C++
class Person {
    virtual const std::string& first_name() = 0;
    virtual const std::string& lame_name() = 0;
    std::string name() { return first_name() + last_name(); }
}
```
(ignore the fact that I'm not putting a space between the names, because that would actually avoid the issue).

